{"term":"1957","caseName":"Giordenello v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/549","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - May 21, 1958 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13494","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 549, Veto Giordenello, Petitioner, versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":34.191,"duration":34.19},{"text":"Mr. Walsh, you may proceed.","start":34.191,"stop":48.738,"duration":14.55}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":48.738,"stop":51.42,"duration":2.68},{"text":"The conviction in this case depends solely upon the admissibility of evidence ceased from the petitioner during an arrest by a federal agent executing a federal warrant of arrest.","start":51.42,"stop":63.998,"duration":12.58},{"text":"There are three issues before the Court.","start":63.998,"stop":67.649,"duration":3.65},{"text":"One, whether the warrant was properly issued and could support a valid arrest, two, whether the petitioner waived is right to object to the validity of the arrest when he waived a preliminary hearing before the United States Commissioner, and three, whether the Government may now rely upon state law to sustain this conviction.","start":67.649,"stop":89.805,"duration":22.16},{"text":"I'm going to go into that in a little more detail later but I would like to say that under state law in Texas, this arrest would not have been lawful under the applicable state statutes where -- as an arrest without a warrant and the cases which we have filed in our reply brief so state.","start":89.805,"stop":108.575,"duration":18.77},{"text":"The facts are these.","start":108.575,"stop":110.742,"duration":2.17},{"text":"A federal narcotics agent named Finley had been investigating the petitioner.","start":110.742,"stop":116.607,"duration":5.86},{"text":"Mr. Finley testified that he had heard that the petitioner was going to Chicago to obtain some heroin and that he had heard also that the petitioner was back in Houston with the heroin.","start":116.607,"stop":128.437,"duration":11.83},{"text":"He said that he had been watching the petitioner since before Christmas of 1955 and that his surveillance corroborated his information to the extent that Giordenello did go to Chicago and did return to Houston.","start":128.437,"stop":142.443,"duration":14.01},{"text":"Mr. Finley admitted at the -- the hearing on this matter that he had no personal knowledge that the petitioner committed any crime.","start":142.443,"stop":150.777,"duration":8.33},{"text":"He said that he had not seen him with narcotics in his possession.","start":150.777,"stop":153.933,"duration":3.16},{"text":"He said that he had never seen him with heroin and that during the entire time he had been following the accused, he had never seen him violate any of the laws of the United States.","start":153.933,"stop":163.708,"duration":9.78},{"text":"Nevertheless, Mr. Finley saw fit to go before United States Commissioner in Houston and filed a complaint in the language of the statute, 21 U.S.C. 174.","start":163.708,"stop":175.248,"duration":11.54},{"text":"It simply alleged that Veto Giordenello did receive, conceal et cetera narcotic drugs to with heroin hydrochloride with knowledge of unlawful importation.","start":175.248,"stop":186.562,"duration":11.31},{"text":"No facts were stated in that complaint.","start":186.562,"stop":190.347,"duration":3.78},{"text":"Mr. Finely did not reveal in that complaint why he thought that the petitioner had received, concealed, et cetera, heroin hydrochloride or anything else.","start":190.347,"stop":200.429,"duration":10.08},{"text":"Obtaining a warrant on the strength of this complaint, Finley followed the petitioner for two days.","start":200.429,"stop":204.78,"duration":4.35},{"text":"He obtained it on the 26th of January, 1956 and shadowed the petitioner until the following day the 27th.","start":204.78,"stop":213.831,"duration":9.05},{"text":"When he saw him coming out of a garage with a paper bag in his hand, and he at that time executed the warrant of arrest.","start":213.831,"stop":222.07,"duration":8.24},{"text":"He claimed that he did not obtain the warrant simply, they have an excuse for arresting the accused but he also claimed that there was no particular reason to execute the warrant at any particular moment or time after obtaining it.","start":222.07,"stop":240.331,"duration":18.26},{"text":"Now, the petitioner was given an opportunity to have a preliminary hearing the following day, the 28th of January.","start":240.331,"stop":248.214,"duration":7.88},{"text":"He had an attorney present with him at the U.S. Commissioner's Office and he waived preliminary hearing.","start":248.214,"stop":255.68,"duration":7.47},{"text":"The attorney who represented him or who accompanied him at that hearing has not appeared again in this case.","start":255.68,"stop":262.331,"duration":6.65},{"text":"He is out of the picture as of the moment that preliminary hearing was waived.","start":262.331,"stop":265.768,"duration":3.44},{"text":"He did not represent Giordenello at the trial or on the appeals of this case.","start":265.768,"stop":272.908,"duration":7.14},{"text":"Giordenello was later indicted not for the offense for which he was arrested, the violation of 21 U.S.C. 174 but for the revenue offense of purchasing narcotics without the appropriate tax-paid stamps.","start":272.908,"stop":287.921,"duration":15.01},{"text":"Shortly after the indictment was returned, the petitioner moved to suppress the evidence ceased during the arrest.","start":287.921,"stop":293.913,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The Government filed no answer to that motion.","start":293.913,"stop":298.997,"duration":5.08},{"text":"A hearing was held before the trial judge at which Mr. Finley testified as a witness called by the petitioner.","start":298.997,"stop":307.84,"duration":8.84},{"text":"Mr. Finely recounted substantially the facts which I have recounted to you.","start":307.84,"stop":314.794,"duration":6.95},{"text":"As I say, the Government did not file any answer to the motion to suppress and the --","start":314.794,"stop":320.298,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":320.298,"stop":330.575,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, in view of the waiver position that the court below took, I don't think the Government is now in a position to sustain this conviction if it did not in the trial court endeavor to establish a waiver.","start":330.575,"stop":346.209,"duration":15.63},{"text":"No argument was made in this -- this -- I was going to go into this little further.","start":346.209,"stop":349.836,"duration":3.63},{"text":"No argument was made by the Government on trial that petitioner waived anything when he waived the preliminary hearing.","start":349.836,"stop":355.282,"duration":5.45},{"text":"Now, the contention that there was a waiver in this case arose for the first time in the Fifth Circuit in the Government's brief.","start":355.282,"stop":363.812,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You think it has application --","start":363.812,"stop":365.699,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I sure do, Your Honor.","start":365.699,"stop":366.827,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":366.827,"stop":367.384,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I do for this reason.","start":367.384,"stop":370.305,"duration":2.92},{"text":"We are discussing his waiver of preliminary hearing based solely upon an entry in the Commissioner's docket which was entered into evidence for other purposes at the trial.","start":370.305,"stop":379.65,"duration":9.34},{"text":"If a man can waive a preliminary -- waive the right to suppress evidence by virtue of waiving a preliminary hearing and I don't think he can.","start":379.65,"stop":387.67,"duration":8.02},{"text":"But if he can, I think it deserves more explanation than we have here.","start":387.67,"stop":393.324,"duration":5.65},{"text":"I think he should have a right to contest for instance whether he was adequately advised by counsel, whether counsel was there representing him or was just standing by.","start":393.324,"stop":401.391,"duration":8.07},{"text":"All of those things I think would require more proof than in this record although as I say, I don't think -- and I'll develop this for the later.","start":401.391,"stop":408.073,"duration":6.68},{"text":"I don't think waiver of preliminary hearing can be waiver of the right to object to an unlawful arrest.","start":408.073,"stop":415.72,"duration":7.65},{"text":"The trial judge overruled the motion to suppress without stating his reasons.","start":415.72,"stop":421.66,"duration":5.94},{"text":"The case proceeded to trial and virtually, the same testimony was elicited by the Government on trial that had been elicited by the defense at the pretrial motion.","start":421.66,"stop":432.746,"duration":11.09},{"text":"At the trial, the United States Attorney succeeded over the objection of the defense in getting the trial judge to take judicial notice that this was an arrest based on a complaint and warrant.","start":432.746,"stop":446.867,"duration":14.12},{"text":"And I think that's significant too in view of the Government's suggestion today that in -- in the Government's brief, that somehow this case could be sustained as though it were a -- an arrest without a warrant made under state law.","start":446.867,"stop":461.098,"duration":14.23},{"text":"I think by taking that strong opposition in the -- in the trial court to the extent of having the judge take judicial notice that the Government cannot now change the issues to the extent that would be necessary to sustain the conviction on those grounds.","start":461.098,"stop":478.836,"duration":17.74},{"text":"Now, I'd like to discuss first the validity of these complaints.","start":478.836,"stop":484.586,"duration":5.75},{"text":"You'll find the complaint, I believe at page 15 in the record.","start":484.586,"stop":492.436,"duration":7.85},{"text":"As I pointed out, the complaint simply alleges the Commission of an offense in the language of a statute.","start":492.436,"stop":499.738,"duration":7.3},{"text":"It has been our position that such a complaint is -- is insufficient, and we've cited considerable authority in our brief to the effect that an affidavit for a warrant must state facts as distinguished from conclusions of law.","start":499.738,"stop":514.558,"duration":14.82},{"text":"The Government's position is that since the language in the indictment of the statute is sufficient, a complaint should be too.","start":514.558,"stop":521.462,"duration":6.9},{"text":"And I say that this ignores the functional and constitutional differences between an indictment and a complaint.","start":521.462,"stop":529.854,"duration":8.39},{"text":"The -- the purpose of these two pleadings is entirely different.","start":529.854,"stop":534.072,"duration":4.22},{"text":"The indictment is evidence of nothing, it is merely an accusation.","start":534.072,"stop":537.984,"duration":3.91},{"text":"It is an expression of the Sixth Amendment right to be advised of the nature of the charge.","start":537.984,"stop":544.058,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Its purpose is only to put a man on notice of what it is he is accused of doing.","start":544.058,"stop":549.242,"duration":5.18},{"text":"The Rule 3 complaint is a different kettle of fish entirely.","start":549.242,"stop":553.819,"duration":4.58},{"text":"The Rule 3 complaint is the constitutional affidavit required by the Fourth Amendment.","start":553.819,"stop":559.736,"duration":5.92},{"text":"In the case of a complaint on which a warrant is issued, the complaint itself is evidence.","start":559.736,"stop":566.077,"duration":6.34},{"text":"The complaint is the basis for the magistrate's decision to issue a warrant.","start":566.077,"stop":571.45,"duration":5.37},{"text":"It's the only basis he has.","start":571.45,"stop":574.428,"duration":2.98},{"text":"And in a case like this, the present situation is simply that Mr. Finley, the narcotics agent, was allowed to determine whether there was probable cause to issue a warrant rather than the magistrate.","start":574.428,"stop":586.242,"duration":11.81},{"text":"The magistrate never knew he accepted Mr. Finley's legal conclusion that the petitioner did receive, conceal, et cetera narcotic drugs, to wit.","start":586.242,"stop":594.593,"duration":8.35},{"text":"The magistrate completely advocated from his function of deciding whether there is a probable cause to the arrest, and that after all is why we have the magistrate.","start":594.593,"stop":606.557,"duration":11.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't warrants -- aren't warrants of arrest issued on the basis of an indictment?","start":606.557,"stop":611.992,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, they are.","start":611.992,"stop":613.38,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well now, you've just indicated it was lost at the very best -- an indictment has freer scope of non-disclosure.","start":613.38,"stop":621.464,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":621.464,"stop":623.119,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind (Voice Overlap) --","start":623.119,"stop":624.334,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you have this, sir.","start":624.334,"stop":628.176,"duration":3.84},{"text":"In the case of an arrest under an indictment, that is a warrant issuing upon an indictment, you at least have the determination of the grand jury that probable cause exists.","start":628.176,"stop":640.63,"duration":12.45},{"text":"You have someone intervening between the policeman and the citizen.","start":640.63,"stop":643.64,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the finding of the grand jury expressed as vaguely as -- it's hypothesized in this complaint.","start":643.64,"stop":650.659,"duration":7.02}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, but it's not -- the point is that it's not the -- the advice portion of it.","start":650.659,"stop":655.622,"duration":4.96},{"text":"The purpose of the indictment and the purpose of the complaint are completely different.","start":655.622,"stop":661.442,"duration":5.82},{"text":"The indictments, you have the -- the grand jury which has heard the evidence and some responsible body had determined that there is probable cause to bring the man to trial.","start":661.442,"stop":670.281,"duration":8.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but it has defined what it has found in a manner or with the vagueness that would be, from your point of view, inadequate to allow the issuance of an -- of arrest that's made in the complaint.","start":670.281,"stop":683.071,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Is that right?","start":683.071,"stop":683.988,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's a fair statement, Your Honor.","start":683.988,"stop":685.431,"duration":1.44},{"text":"I sure do.","start":685.431,"stop":686.434,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":686.434,"stop":687.171,"duration":0.74},{"text":"That was disturbing (Voice Overlap) --","start":687.171,"stop":688.495,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":688.495,"stop":689.424,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the practice, Mr. Walsh, in the federal system?","start":689.424,"stop":693.8,"duration":4.38},{"text":"I know in the state system for instance, this practice is a common thing.","start":693.8,"stop":699.296,"duration":5.5},{"text":"It says to allege the ultimate fact that -- that it shall be or whatever happens to be but in the federal system, what is the -- what is the practice as to -- as to complaints.","start":699.296,"stop":712.88,"duration":13.58},{"text":"Do they set forth with the -- the facts to establish the offense or do they just allege the ultimate fact?","start":712.88,"stop":721.613,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would hesitate, Your Honor, to speculate as to what the overall federal practice is.","start":721.613,"stop":727.36,"duration":5.75},{"text":"I think the case has clearly established that if that warrant is to be valid, the complaint must actually set out the evidentiary basis upon which the officer desires to make an arrest so that the magistrate from reading the complaint, can determine whether or not there is probable cause.","start":727.36,"stop":746.92,"duration":19.56},{"text":"This completely short circuits the magistrate.","start":746.92,"stop":749.312,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":749.312,"stop":749.57,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we've cited quite a few cases in our brief to that affect that -- and have an appendix of -- of cases which discusses that at some length.","start":749.57,"stop":760.076,"duration":10.51},{"text":"The Court will see two complaints in -- in Steele versus United States in the 267 U.S. and in Dumbra verus United States in the 268 U.S.","start":760.076,"stop":770.977,"duration":10.9},{"text":"We'll see two complaints which the Court has approved as being sufficient and they are both quite detailed as to their analysis of the facts.","start":770.977,"stop":786.322,"duration":15.35},{"text":"If Finley really knew the things which he said he knew at the time he obtained that warrant, he could easily have stated them in the complaint and --","start":786.322,"stop":797.302,"duration":10.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":797.302,"stop":802.233,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"In the complaints, Your Honor.","start":802.233,"stop":803.525,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":803.525,"stop":805.38,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":805.38,"stop":805.926,"duration":0.55},{"text":"If he knew those things, we would have an entirely -- in our brief, we go into the question also of whether you can get a warrant at all based on personal knowledge.","start":805.926,"stop":814.166,"duration":8.24},{"text":"But actually, it isn't necessary to develop that fully in order to refer to this case because Mr. Finley didn't even tell us hearsay to the magistrate.","start":814.166,"stop":823.357,"duration":9.19},{"text":"If he had filed a complaint saying, “I've heard that Veto Giordenello was going to Chicago to buy heroin and I know that he's gone up there and he's come back,\" and so on, then we would have a case where it would be necessary to determine whether the hearsay was sufficient nor to authorize the issuance of a warrant.","start":823.357,"stop":838.006,"duration":14.65},{"text":"But here, Mr. Finley did not even give his scanty information such as it was to the magistrate.","start":838.006,"stop":845.27,"duration":7.26},{"text":"And --","start":845.27,"stop":846.229,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":846.229,"stop":849.99,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the cases hold that the complaint is -- must be self-sufficient and -- and cannot be bolstered up by oral testimony.","start":849.99,"stop":858.496,"duration":8.51},{"text":"I'd like to discuss the waiver aspect of this case briefly.","start":858.496,"stop":863.111,"duration":4.62},{"text":"As I say the waiver question was raised first by -- in the Fifth Circuit by the Government.","start":863.111,"stop":871.835,"duration":8.72},{"text":"I think it's extremely significant that Giordenello was not -- and to this day, has not been charged or indicted or tried or anything for the offense for which he was arrested.","start":871.835,"stop":884.295,"duration":12.46},{"text":"To this day, no indictment has been filed under that violation of 21 U.S.C. 174, and yet they are -- the Government is arguing that the petitioner's actions in a case completely unrelated to the -- at least legally unrelated to the case which you are now reviewing, should in some way control this case.","start":884.295,"stop":909.8,"duration":25.5},{"text":"I don't think that's proper.","start":909.8,"stop":910.715,"duration":0.92},{"text":"I think in any event, a man ought to have a right to decide in a particular case what -- what it is he wants to do without committing himself as to all future cases.","start":910.715,"stop":918.845,"duration":8.13},{"text":"And let me observe that there is pending in this Court as number 515 miscellaneous a conspiracy case involving the same evidence, it was used again as evidence in a -- an indictment returned almost six months after the arrest.","start":918.845,"stop":933.012,"duration":14.17},{"text":"Now, can it fairly be said that a man is making a knowing intelligent waiver of anything when he is not even charged with the crime at which the evidence is to be used, I don't think so.","start":933.012,"stop":945.553,"duration":12.54},{"text":"The -- I -- I think even if he were tried for the offense which -- for which he was allegedly arrested, I -- I don't think that waiver of preliminary hearing can amount to consent to an arrest.","start":945.553,"stop":964.807,"duration":19.25},{"text":"The Government is actually asking you to take that position.","start":964.807,"stop":967.011,"duration":2.2},{"text":"They are saying, “By waiving preliminary hearing, petitioner in effect admitted through counsel that Finley did have sufficient basis to arrest him.”","start":967.011,"stop":974.494,"duration":7.48},{"text":"Now, I think that's a pretty extreme view and it's going to have the considerable effect on the administration of justice in the federal courts if you agree with it.","start":974.494,"stop":983.292,"duration":8.8},{"text":"I say that for this reason, a large number of these hearings are waived.","start":983.292,"stop":988.599,"duration":5.31},{"text":"It is very seldom that counsel who tries a case is in on it in time to represent a man the day after the arrest.","start":988.599,"stop":995.712,"duration":7.11},{"text":"If for no other reason, it usually takes a man time to get a fee together.","start":995.712,"stop":1002.243,"duration":6.53},{"text":"If we hold the man, the waivers made at these preliminary hearings, everybody will have to demand a preliminary hearing and go through the whole business and try his case twice.","start":1002.243,"stop":1011.43,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And that is going to tie up United States Commissioners all over the country.","start":1011.43,"stop":1015.242,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Furthermore --","start":1015.242,"stop":1016.664,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, people don't waive hearings merely in order to expedite hearings and get to your trial on the merits, the rehearings for all sorts of cases?","start":1016.664,"stop":1026.809,"duration":10.14}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I personally don't waive hearings, Your Honor, but --","start":1026.809,"stop":1028.819,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm not -- but I mean hearings are waived not merely because primarily -- because defendant (Inaudible) greatly interest, did he, in the efficient administration of criminal justice?","start":1028.819,"stop":1040.108,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, but they are waived primarily.","start":1040.108,"stop":1041.796,"duration":1.69},{"text":"And as a general rule by people who simply want to have their bails set and get out, they are able to make their bail and they just don't want to stay in and fool around when they think they have a trial coming up.","start":1041.796,"stop":1053.365,"duration":11.57},{"text":"If you affirm this case, he isn't going to have the trial coming up.","start":1053.365,"stop":1057.627,"duration":4.26},{"text":"There are number of -- the whole thing really been decided at the preliminary hearing.","start":1057.627,"stop":1062.292,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1062.292,"stop":1066.951,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"He would have committed himself --","start":1066.951,"stop":1068.652,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1068.652,"stop":1072.972,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and I don't how far the Government is asking you to carry that through, Your Honor.","start":1072.972,"stop":1080.723,"duration":7.75},{"text":"You get into a lot of other questions, what if a man comes without counsel and the U.S. Commissioner advices him that he has a right to counsel and he waives counsel and says -- go ahead let's set the bond, and waives the whole preliminary hearing himself has he then waived everything which a lawyer could have done if a lawyer had been there?","start":1080.723,"stop":1101.15,"duration":20.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm a little startled by the -- what you say as the Government's contention.","start":1101.15,"stop":1104.68,"duration":3.53},{"text":"What is the state of the law in the lower court?","start":1104.68,"stop":1107.048,"duration":2.37},{"text":"So the question certainly hasn't come before us.","start":1107.048,"stop":1110.005,"duration":2.96},{"text":"What -- what is the rulings of the lower courts before the Courts of Appeals or the District Courts?","start":1110.005,"stop":1117.221,"duration":7.22}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"On the question of waiver?","start":1117.221,"stop":1118.569,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On whether because he waived a -- by waiving -- by -- by not having a preliminary hearing, he waived the infirmities leading to the arrest?","start":1118.569,"stop":1128.939,"duration":10.37}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the state of the law is this, Your Honor.","start":1128.939,"stop":1131.486,"duration":2.55},{"text":"There are not more than four or five cases dealing with this question.","start":1131.486,"stop":1135.717,"duration":4.23},{"text":"One of them is United States versus Walker which is cited, it's in our brief, the 197 F.2d and decided in all of our briefs.","start":1135.717,"stop":1145.977,"duration":10.26},{"text":"Walker was a collateral attack but the Court was not directly considering his problem.","start":1145.977,"stop":1150.914,"duration":4.94},{"text":"They held that when the man waived preliminary -- actually, it was a removal proceeding that he waived.","start":1150.914,"stop":1156.783,"duration":5.87},{"text":"Now, that is patently wrong.","start":1156.783,"stop":1158.979,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Rule 41(e) clearly provides the man may make a motion to suppress either in the District Court in which he is arrested or the court in which trial is to be held.","start":1158.979,"stop":1168.306,"duration":9.33},{"text":"And clearly, the Walker case is -- simply, it doesn't mention Rule 41(e) at all and -- and takes no account of it.","start":1168.306,"stop":1174.785,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I was brought up to believe that that it's mostly valuable to encourage going to the place of trail instead of trying things out at the place of arrest for a removal.","start":1174.785,"stop":1185.987,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I was too, Your Honor.","start":1185.987,"stop":1193.609,"duration":7.62},{"text":"The --- the only case that --","start":1193.609,"stop":1194.883,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1194.883,"stop":1195.233,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"-- we have here what I think --","start":1195.233,"stop":1195.98,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You said there were four.","start":1195.98,"stop":1197.452,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1197.452,"stop":1197.987,"duration":0.54},{"text":"There is United States versus -- I believe it's pronounced (Inaudible) which again is cited in the briefs.","start":1197.987,"stop":1203.706,"duration":5.72},{"text":"I believe the Government cited it.","start":1203.706,"stop":1207.923,"duration":4.22},{"text":"That case holds that by waiving preliminary hearing, you do waive such technical defects as spelling of names and things like that.","start":1207.923,"stop":1215.706,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Now, it is my position that this is not just a technicality.","start":1215.706,"stop":1219.247,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Here in -- the defect in this warrant goes to the very heart of our system under the Fourth Amendment.","start":1219.247,"stop":1225.052,"duration":5.8},{"text":"And Judge Hand, writing that opinion, says that the petitioner is waiving only formalities.","start":1225.052,"stop":1235.444,"duration":10.39},{"text":"By waiving the preliminary hearing, he's simply waiving the right to have a --","start":1235.444,"stop":1238.142,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the one that Judge Reeds dealt with and quoted at length in Judge Hand's (Voice Overlap)?","start":1238.142,"stop":1242.52,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, it sure is.","start":1242.52,"stop":1243.727,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that's -- I think that that carries it very far on this problem.","start":1243.727,"stop":1247.083,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I say, there aren't many cases on this, Your Honor.","start":1247.083,"stop":1252.331,"duration":5.25},{"text":"As a matter of fact, Walker and (Inaudible) are the only two that that deal directly with this thing that I've been able to find in my research.","start":1252.331,"stop":1261.994,"duration":9.66},{"text":"The question of state law raised by the Government for the first time here, there is a statute in Texas which purports to allow narcotics officers to make such as for contraband.","start":1261.994,"stop":1275.731,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't -- you -- you challenge the Government -- disagree with the Government that in the absence of a federal statute of this, I -- because this, because I know not.","start":1275.731,"stop":1285.233,"duration":9.5},{"text":"The local law of arrest determines the federal light for arrest.","start":1285.233,"stop":1289.837,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I disagree with it, Your Honor --","start":1289.837,"stop":1290.795,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1290.795,"stop":1291.19,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but it's -- it's really not necessary to develop it for this case because the Texas case has clearly established that under Texas law, this would be an unlawful arrest.","start":1291.19,"stop":1298.039,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I thought they decided that in -- whatever it was, Di Re or --","start":1298.039,"stop":1301.427,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it was decided in Di Re and Johnson only that for the purpose of evidence which in existence in the hands of a state police officer.","start":1301.427,"stop":1312.613,"duration":11.19},{"text":"In testing its -- it's admissibility in the federal courts if used there, we would apply the state standards.","start":1312.613,"stop":1319.159,"duration":6.55},{"text":"But this Court has never held that a state may enlarge the powers of a federal officer or that a federal officer's -- pardon I -- as a matter fact claimed that under Di Re versus United States, the federal officer's job is to follow the federal rules and -- and he is not entitled.","start":1319.159,"stop":1336.091,"duration":16.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say it is a federal rule, but I -- I just want to be corrected.","start":1336.091,"stop":1340.481,"duration":4.39},{"text":"But I thought the whole problem of Di Re was, since there is no federal legislation and no determination by this Court in formulating general rules of criminal procedure.","start":1340.481,"stop":1353.215,"duration":12.73},{"text":"In order to ascertain the validity of an arrest, you go not unnaturally to what the local law of arrest.","start":1353.215,"stop":1360.258,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":1360.258,"stop":1360.626,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- if I exaggerated it --","start":1360.626,"stop":1363.502,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you have it slightly, Your Honor.","start":1363.502,"stop":1365.431,"duration":1.93},{"text":"I -- I feel that all that case decides is that evidence ceased by a state policeman will be tested according the state standards.","start":1365.431,"stop":1373.455,"duration":8.02},{"text":"But here in effect, we have a federal statute.","start":1373.455,"stop":1377.928,"duration":4.47},{"text":"We have the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure.","start":1377.928,"stop":1379.385,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But then, don't waste your time because you've said --","start":1379.385,"stop":1381.284,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1381.284,"stop":1381.493,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Texas law is with you.","start":1381.493,"stop":1382.978,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1382.978,"stop":1383.298,"duration":0.32},{"text":"The Texas law I think is with me.","start":1383.298,"stop":1385.282,"duration":1.98},{"text":"I cited two cases in the reply brief which I filed, Giacona versus State and Harper versus State, page 2 in the reply brief.","start":1385.282,"stop":1396.878,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Giocona is a paper --","start":1396.878,"stop":1397.767,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I should think that you've embraced the reading.","start":1397.767,"stop":1401.941,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sir, I -- I don't think this arrest could be justified under anybody's standards.","start":1401.941,"stop":1404.998,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1404.998,"stop":1406.55,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Giocona versus State is a brown paper bag case which gets about as close to this one as you can.","start":1406.55,"stop":1411.394,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Rosie Giacona was sitting in an automobile with a brown paper bag in her hand and officers were making an arrest of another person in the car with her.","start":1411.394,"stop":1421.762,"duration":10.37},{"text":"The Court of Criminal Appeals said that she herself must commit some act in their presence in order to make the arrest lawful no matter how much information they had about her.","start":1421.762,"stop":1430.837,"duration":9.08},{"text":"And the Pee Wee--Harper case is the same thing.","start":1430.837,"stop":1433.102,"duration":2.27},{"text":"Now, there was no act on the part of this defendant, in Mr. Finley's presence.","start":1433.102,"stop":1438.242,"duration":5.14},{"text":"Mr. Finley had no way of knowing what was in the paper bag.","start":1438.242,"stop":1441.813,"duration":3.57},{"text":"And I -- I believe that the Harper and Giacona cases will satisfy the Court that state law does not authorize this arrest.","start":1441.813,"stop":1450.278,"duration":8.46},{"text":"I think I'll save the rest of my time for rebuttal, if I may.","start":1450.278,"stop":1453.028,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":1453.028,"stop":1457.623,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Mr. Murphy.","start":1457.623,"stop":1465.691,"duration":8.07}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1465.691,"stop":1473.521,"duration":7.83},{"text":"The issue in this case is solely one of the admissibility of a large quantity of heroin hydrochloride ceased from the petitioner on January 27th, 1956 at which time he was arrested under a warrant issued the previous day by a United States Commissioner, which warrant was supported by a complaint which charged the petitioner with receiving and concealing heroin hydrochloride in violation of Section 174 of Title 21.","start":1473.521,"stop":1518.242,"duration":44.72},{"text":"The petitioner contends that the evidence was inadmissible because it was obtained as a result of an unlawful arrest.","start":1518.242,"stop":1529.509,"duration":11.27},{"text":"He contends that the arrest was unlawful because the warrant upon which it was purported to have been made was not supported by a complaint satisfying the requirements of Rule 3 of the Federal Rules, and also that the complainant did not have personal knowledge of the facts alleged in the complaint.","start":1529.509,"stop":1552.165,"duration":22.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not questioned that if the arrest was legal, the search was valid.","start":1552.165,"stop":1557.28,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"That is precisely true, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1557.28,"stop":1559.837,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It all turns under it.","start":1559.837,"stop":1560.894,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"It turns on the validity of the arrest.","start":1560.894,"stop":1564.457,"duration":3.56},{"text":"The Government of course supports the legally of the arrest.","start":1564.457,"stop":1570.19,"duration":5.73},{"text":"It does this under several theories or on double basis.","start":1570.19,"stop":1577.835,"duration":7.64},{"text":"First, it contends that the arrest was lawful under state law.","start":1577.835,"stop":1585.122,"duration":7.29},{"text":"We of course must look to the state law to determine the legality of arrest where there is no federal statute authorizing a federal officer to make an arrest without warrant.","start":1585.122,"stop":1599.81,"duration":14.69},{"text":"The Di Re case, I think Mr. Justice Frankfurter correctly interprets as so holding.","start":1599.81,"stop":1607.934,"duration":8.12},{"text":"And incidentally in that case, I believe there was a federal officer present so that it is precisely in point here.","start":1607.934,"stop":1617.308,"duration":9.37},{"text":"The particular statute of the State of Texas upon which the Government relies is set forth at page 2 of our brief and it is Article 725 (b) of the Texas Penal Code.","start":1617.308,"stop":1635.414,"duration":18.11},{"text":"Now, we did not raise this issue precisely in the court below at that time, we were under the impression that we had to rely upon Article 212 of the Code of Criminal Procedure of the State of Texas which permits arrest by a private person where the felony is being committed in his presence and he has reasonable grounds to believe that the defendant is about to escape.","start":1635.414,"stop":1666.486,"duration":31.07},{"text":"In this instance of course, no contention was made by the Government that the officer had reasonable grounds to believe that an escape was going to be attempted so we did not attempt to justify the arrest under that statute.","start":1666.486,"stop":1681.553,"duration":15.07},{"text":"Nor did we attempt to justify the arrest or do we attempt to justify the arrest in this Court upon the basis that the officer could have observed the crime being committed in his presence.","start":1681.553,"stop":1696.683,"duration":15.13},{"text":"Although, I must say that the interpretation of the court below in that regard which can be found in the opinion which is printed in the record and the particular portion to which I allude is at page 65, the court below did undertake by way of dicta of course because its real holding was placed upon the waiver theory.","start":1696.683,"stop":1723.425,"duration":26.74},{"text":"But it did say that moreover, there was enough in the record to make it clear that an honest official might well have thought he was fully observing the legal restraints placed upon his actions and that he had good cause for arrest.","start":1723.425,"stop":1735.317,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Even if the warrant already obtained was invalid since he believed he saw a felony being committed in his presence, a belief that subsequent events proved to be true.","start":1735.317,"stop":1746.666,"duration":11.35},{"text":"Now, the -- as I've said, the -- the Government first supports the conviction of the petitioner upon the basis that the arrest was valid under Texas state law.","start":1746.666,"stop":1761.115,"duration":14.45},{"text":"Now, article --","start":1761.115,"stop":1761.641,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you say the word amounts to cases that Mr. Walsh vouches for his own position?","start":1761.641,"stop":1766.948,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the -- the law is very sparse on the point, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1766.948,"stop":1773.573,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Of course the leading case is Walker and that holds squarely --","start":1773.573,"stop":1776.958,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I just the Texas law.","start":1776.958,"stop":1779.639,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1779.639,"stop":1780.465,"duration":0.83},{"text":"The -- the Texas State cases are -- they are also cited in our brief incidentally and we rely on them.","start":1780.465,"stop":1788.56,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) in his reply brief as getting Texas law in his favor.","start":1788.56,"stop":1793.704,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Giacona and Harper are the two Texas cases which -- to which he refers of course.","start":1793.704,"stop":1800.147,"duration":6.44},{"text":"And in Harper of course, there was absolutely no probable cause for the arrest.","start":1800.147,"stop":1806.147,"duration":6},{"text":"A previously convicted narcotic violator was observed by police officers sitting in his car, and that was the sole basis for the arrest.","start":1806.147,"stop":1816.487,"duration":10.34},{"text":"The -- the officer attempted to justify it on some suspicious grounds but really, the essential basis upon which he made the arrest was pure suspicion, and we don't adopt that case at all.","start":1816.487,"stop":1832.466,"duration":15.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean the cases but it makes a lot of deference, but the -- the Texas Court said that on the facts, there was no probable cause or whether the Texas Court said something else which is what I gather from Mr. Walsh's account of it.","start":1832.466,"stop":1846.603,"duration":14.14}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I believe that the Harper case holds squarely on the facts, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1846.603,"stop":1851.755,"duration":5.15},{"text":"The Giacona --","start":1851.755,"stop":1852.097,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it printed in your brief?","start":1852.097,"stop":1854.153,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Harper is not.","start":1854.153,"stop":1855.403,"duration":1.25},{"text":"Harper is not, Giacona is.","start":1855.403,"stop":1858.37,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Harper.","start":1858.37,"stop":1861.123,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me, sir.","start":1861.123,"stop":1861.318,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Harper.","start":1861.318,"stop":1862.512,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't find the Harper (Voice Overlap) other brief.","start":1862.512,"stop":1863.742,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's in, Mr. Walsh's brief 284 S.W.2d.","start":1863.742,"stop":1867.89,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"284.","start":1867.89,"stop":1868.828,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the name under which it is printed?","start":1868.828,"stop":1870.219,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Harper.","start":1870.219,"stop":1870.481,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Harper against States, cited at page 2 of the reply brief.","start":1870.481,"stop":1874.077,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the reply brief.","start":1874.077,"stop":1879.219,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in --","start":1879.219,"stop":1880.377,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the other one?","start":1880.377,"stop":1881.982,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Giacona.","start":1881.982,"stop":1883.373,"duration":1.39},{"text":"Again, there was a very unfavorable factual situation.","start":1883.373,"stop":1890.713,"duration":7.34},{"text":"The officers merely had information that Giacona was in possession of some marijuana and that his car was going to arrive at a particular parking lot at a certain time and going there, they observed him drive into the parking lot and at that time, placed him under arrest.","start":1890.713,"stop":1916.048,"duration":25.34},{"text":"They also arrested his wife Rosie Giacona who was the defendant in the Giacona case.","start":1916.048,"stop":1922.349,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Her husband Pete, I believe, had pled guilty.","start":1922.349,"stop":1926.387,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Rosie Giacona contended that the officers had no reason to arrest her because they had no probable cause to believe that she was in possession of any contraband.","start":1926.387,"stop":1935.663,"duration":9.28},{"text":"And I believe that again, we have a -- two factual situation.","start":1935.663,"stop":1941.995,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say that your facts, that if one reads the record, it would come in what Mr. Walsh spoke from Thomas against State that the officer have some information that the accuse of violating the law plus some act on the part of the accused, which would bolster it before Judge --","start":1941.995,"stop":1960.652,"duration":18.66}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"We do, Your Honor.","start":1960.652,"stop":1963.029,"duration":2.38},{"text":"However, Mr. Walsh I think extends the Texas cases beyond the point to which they have gone in contending that the fact which must observed must be an incriminating fact.","start":1963.029,"stop":1976.514,"duration":13.48},{"text":"The -- the fact as we contend simply must be one which corroborates his prior information.","start":1976.514,"stop":1983.715,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Perhaps I should at this point recount the facts upon which the agent purported to act.","start":1983.715,"stop":1993.392,"duration":9.68},{"text":"As Mr. Walsh has pointed out, the investigation commenced about a month prior to the date of his arrest.","start":1993.392,"stop":2001.716,"duration":8.32},{"text":"It was engendered by information received from various sources and it continued for a period of approximately one month during which time the agent received information from other law enforcement officers and that information was to the effect that Giordenello was in possession -- I'm reading now from page 18 of the record, about two thirds of the way down.","start":2001.716,"stop":2038.708,"duration":36.99},{"text":"There is testimony by agent Finley who made the arrest as to what was the basis of his information.","start":2038.708,"stop":2047.544,"duration":8.84},{"text":"And at this point, before I read it, I would like to point this out, that the Government is here compelled to defend the arrest and to support the arrest upon probable cause upon a record made by the petitioner.","start":2047.544,"stop":2067.556,"duration":20.01},{"text":"This is so because this record was made in a motion to suppress here at which point during which hearing of course the petitioner had the burden of proof of showing lack of probable cause.","start":2067.556,"stop":2082.369,"duration":14.81},{"text":"Had he not waived his preliminary hearing and had he insisted upon that proceeding, the Government would have had the burden of proof of showing probable cause and in justification of the arrest.","start":2082.369,"stop":2096.409,"duration":14.04},{"text":"And of course the Government attorney having such a burden would not have done I think what he did in the suppression hearing.","start":2096.409,"stop":2104.488,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But nothing -- but nothing prevents the Government in a suppression hearing to pile up the evidence even though the burden is on the other fellow.","start":2104.488,"stop":2111.357,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, but the Government attorney was understandably reluctant, I believe, to bring out all of the evidentiary details.","start":2111.357,"stop":2121.623,"duration":10.27},{"text":"If petitioner was unwilling to bring them out, there was no compulsion upon him to do it.","start":2121.623,"stop":2126.109,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The burden was on the petitioner to -- to establish lack of probable cause.","start":2126.109,"stop":2131.012,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what federal (Inaudible).","start":2131.012,"stop":2134.482,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2134.482,"stop":2134.791,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you -- do you rely on the warrant of arrest that this officer had or do you rely under some theory?","start":2134.791,"stop":2141.985,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"We rely on both, Your Honor.","start":2141.985,"stop":2143.293,"duration":1.31},{"text":"We say that first of all, it can be justified under Texas law irrespective of the warrant.","start":2143.293,"stop":2148.371,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2148.371,"stop":2148.606,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Secondly, that the warrant was valid.","start":2148.606,"stop":2150.543,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2150.543,"stop":2150.873,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"And thirdly, that even if the warrant were not valid that he waived its invalidity.","start":2150.873,"stop":2157.393,"duration":6.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2157.393,"stop":2157.557,"duration":0.16},{"text":"I'd like to ask you the question I asked Mr. Walsh about the prerequisites of a complaint and what that complaint must show.","start":2157.557,"stop":2166.379,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"The requisites of a complaint are stated in Rule 3 of the Federal Rules, and we cite Rule 3 at page 3 of our brief insofar as it's applicable here.","start":2166.379,"stop":2182.813,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I should think you would begin earlier and begin with the Constitution.","start":2182.813,"stop":2186.408,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well of course, we -- we must assume that the arrest must be justified on -- upon constitutional grounds and no warrants shall issue but upon probable cause.","start":2186.408,"stop":2197.03,"duration":10.62},{"text":"The question of course is not what the complaint said or what the warrant said but what the Commissioner knew.","start":2197.03,"stop":2206.736,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Now, I might say at this point that the -- the petitioner's counsel very outrightly and skillfully did not bring out the facts of what the Commissioner knew.","start":2206.736,"stop":2216.703,"duration":9.97},{"text":"He preferred to base his questions upon a theory that he had at that time that he thought was valid, namely that the agent did not have personal knowledge of the facts which he alleged in his complaint.","start":2216.703,"stop":2231.26,"duration":14.56},{"text":"Then I may say this that the contention now made by the petitioner that the complaint did not state essential facts, was not made during the trial, it was made for the first time in a motion for a new trial.","start":2231.26,"stop":2246.203,"duration":14.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'd like to know is what -- what must the complaint contain?","start":2246.203,"stop":2251.615,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"In our view, the complaint must contain no more than what was contained in this complaint in this case which said, William E. Finley, agent, Bureau of Narcotics being duly sworn does state that Veto Giordenello did on the 27th day of January 1956 or 26th day of January 1956 received and concealed heroin hydrochloride in violation of 21 U.S.C. 174.","start":2251.615,"stop":2282.206,"duration":30.59},{"text":"Now, we --","start":2282.206,"stop":2283.259,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, do the case has support you in that?","start":2283.259,"stop":2286.568,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they do, Your Honor.","start":2286.568,"stop":2288.219,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What case do you rely on particularly?","start":2288.219,"stop":2290.426,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we rely on several cases.","start":2290.426,"stop":2295.054,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But there's one --","start":2295.054,"stop":2295.824,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"For instance --","start":2295.824,"stop":2296.114,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's directly in point?","start":2296.114,"stop":2297.312,"duration":1.2},{"text":"If you have one that's in point.","start":2297.312,"stop":2300.703,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is a Dolan case, I'm not sure if we cited that in our brief.","start":2300.703,"stop":2309.475,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Walker of course --","start":2309.475,"stop":2309.84,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But one -- one whom you didn't -- one that was directly in point and you didn't cite it?","start":2309.84,"stop":2313.559,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there -- the law on this subject is very sparse, you see the -- the --","start":2313.559,"stop":2322.391,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all the more reason why I would think you would cite it if it's directly in point?","start":2322.391,"stop":2330.922,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, the -- yes, the Lonsdale case cited at -- now, I just wouldn't cite that one either.","start":2330.922,"stop":2348.908,"duration":17.99},{"text":"Mr. Walsh cited Lonsdale and of course, we didn't rely on Lonsdale because that was a peculiar case.","start":2348.908,"stop":2358.149,"duration":9.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You did or you did not?","start":2358.149,"stop":2359.114,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"We did not.","start":2359.114,"stop":2360.456,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But what one do you rely on?","start":2360.456,"stop":2361.733,"duration":1.28},{"text":"That's what I want to know.","start":2361.733,"stop":2362.268,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you see, we rely upon Walker below.","start":2362.268,"stop":2367.663,"duration":5.39},{"text":"And the Walker case, the opinion does not set forth the gist of the complaint.","start":2367.663,"stop":2375.622,"duration":7.96},{"text":"That -- that is, it doesn't set forth the complaint in its entirety and the holding of the Walker case is of course that the --","start":2375.622,"stop":2382.14,"duration":6.52}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2382.14,"stop":2384.158,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, it's a Second Circuit decision reported at, I believe 197 F.2d.","start":2384.158,"stop":2393.654,"duration":9.5},{"text":"There have been some lower court cases that I --","start":2393.654,"stop":2397.886,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now, Mr. Murphy.","start":2397.886,"stop":2403.465,"duration":5.58}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - May 21, 1958 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13514","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may proceed, Mr. Murphy.","start":0,"stop":5.058,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I believe I may have missed the precise import of your question just before we adjourned.","start":5.058,"stop":17.443,"duration":12.39},{"text":"As I understand it, you wish to know which cases the Government relies on as supporting the proposition that a complaint stated in the terms of a statute would be sufficient.","start":17.443,"stop":33.849,"duration":16.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"As you have stated here, yes.","start":33.849,"stop":35.356,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":35.356,"stop":35.955,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":35.955,"stop":36.382,"duration":0.43},{"text":"That was right.","start":36.382,"stop":37.508,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"We rely upon the Walker case for that proposition.","start":37.508,"stop":42.356,"duration":4.85},{"text":"And of course, we also rely for the --","start":42.356,"stop":46.031,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is not in your brief though, is it?","start":46.031,"stop":47.538,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is, --","start":47.538,"stop":48.317,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, is it?","start":48.317,"stop":49.413,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Mr. Chief Justice.","start":49.413,"stop":50.619,"duration":1.21},{"text":"It's cited at various places.","start":50.619,"stop":51.884,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, all right.","start":51.884,"stop":52.573,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"The particular point is -- is made at page 30 of our brief.","start":52.573,"stop":60.197,"duration":7.62},{"text":"And of course, other cases are cited at that place in our brief, page 30, which support the proposition that an indictment in the language of a statute will suffice.","start":60.197,"stop":73.487,"duration":13.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":73.487,"stop":74.625,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, this --","start":74.625,"stop":74.825,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a difference in the duty, do you think?","start":74.825,"stop":78.236,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"There should not be, Mr. Justice Black.","start":78.236,"stop":80.672,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You think it's not.","start":80.672,"stop":82.429,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"The two rules -- rules -- the form of the indictment as governed by Rule 7 (c) of the Criminal rules and its language is practically identical to Rule 3.","start":82.429,"stop":95.53,"duration":13.1},{"text":"And it again requires that the essential facts of the crime be stated and we see no reason why a different interpretation should be placed upon the phrase \"essential facts\" in one rule and in the other.","start":95.53,"stop":112.293,"duration":16.76},{"text":"They are --","start":112.293,"stop":112.72,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I think in page 30 of your brief, I see those are all Court of Appeals cases, you have none from this Court from which you rely on at this point, is it?","start":112.72,"stop":125.204,"duration":12.48}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":125.204,"stop":126.542,"duration":1.34},{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":126.542,"stop":127.099,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you, Mr. Murphy, you made some statement, I misunderstood almost to the effect that the Commissioner had more data before him than this application for the warrant indicated.","start":127.099,"stop":144.185,"duration":17.09}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"The point I made, Mr. Justice Harlan, was that there was nothing in the record to show that the Commissioner did not have additional facts before him than were contained in the complaint.","start":144.185,"stop":157.917,"duration":13.73},{"text":"If we -- I think shouldn't --","start":157.917,"stop":158.925,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that should -- that goes to your waiver point, does it?","start":158.925,"stop":161.476,"duration":2.55},{"text":"Your --","start":161.476,"stop":163.362,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":163.362,"stop":163.492,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- waiver argument.","start":163.492,"stop":163.851,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"And it also goes to the validity of the complaint and warrant point also, because the Commissioner is under an admonition in his own manual that he should not issue a warrant upon the mere suggestion of a complaining witness.","start":163.851,"stop":184.113,"duration":20.26},{"text":"He should examine the witness under oath both the complainant and any other witnesses.","start":184.113,"stop":189.984,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did he do that here?","start":189.984,"stop":191.898,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"There was nothing to show that he did nor that he did not.","start":191.898,"stop":196.06,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You have this assumption --","start":196.06,"stop":198.683,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, we -- we rely on an assumption of regularity of the proceedings --","start":198.683,"stop":202.014,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you stand on what the record shows, don't you?","start":202.014,"stop":205.956,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we do stand on it, Your Honor, but Mr. Walsh of course made a point that no facts were communicated to the Commissioner.","start":205.956,"stop":216.085,"duration":10.13},{"text":"To make -- to draw that conclusion you would have to assume that the Commissioner didn't do his duty.","start":216.085,"stop":221.225,"duration":5.14},{"text":"I think that a presumption of regularity to that effect surrounds the Commissioner's proceedings.","start":221.225,"stop":226.712,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But then the assumption would validate every requirement, wouldn't it?","start":226.712,"stop":229.955,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Because you -- one must assume whatever the record shows there was enough for the Commissioner to issue the warrant.","start":229.955,"stop":235.961,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":235.961,"stop":236.548,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that true?","start":236.548,"stop":237.444,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"In the absence of evidence to the contrary, yes, Your Honor.","start":237.444,"stop":240.738,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That as you say that it's up to the --","start":240.738,"stop":244.339,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"It's up to --","start":244.339,"stop":244.537,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- rest to defendant who affirmatively there was nothing (Voice Overlap) to the Commissioner.","start":244.537,"stop":249.555,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it -- depending on -- Mr. Justice Frankfurter, depending on where he raises it.","start":249.555,"stop":254.463,"duration":4.91},{"text":"If he raises it at the preliminary hearing then it's incumbent upon the Government to go forward and prove what was before the Commissioner.","start":254.463,"stop":261.199,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The implication of that is that there is some compulsion or some compartment to have -- to have a preliminary hearing not to dispense with it but with some --","start":261.199,"stop":270.543,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"If he wish it --","start":270.543,"stop":271.541,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- some pressure on it.","start":271.541,"stop":273.298,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"If he wishes to raise the regularity of his arrest.","start":273.298,"stop":276.789,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He has a choice not to.","start":276.789,"stop":278.276,"duration":1.49},{"text":"He considers a waiver hearing right now.","start":278.276,"stop":280.973,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Did he ever agrees to everything else that goes along with it?","start":280.973,"stop":283.616,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we say that he waives the regularity --","start":283.616,"stop":286.718,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- the question is whether he waived?","start":286.718,"stop":288.981,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"He waives the regularity of his arrest that we say he waives any technical infirmity or defect in the complaint.","start":288.981,"stop":297.903,"duration":8.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"From that spelling of the complaint, you know, I covered these cases, that's one thing.","start":297.903,"stop":302.422,"duration":4.52},{"text":"But does he waive the process by which he's supposed to meet legally before a -- before the federal authority, (Voice Overlap)?","start":302.422,"stop":310.93,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Both --","start":310.93,"stop":312.585,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What does waiver mean in that sense?","start":312.585,"stop":315.328,"duration":2.74},{"text":"It means, that's what you use.","start":315.328,"stop":316.653,"duration":1.33},{"text":"It means that an implication of law if he doesn't take advantage of saying I want -- I want a jury, it's an implication of law that the -- he underwrites everything up to that point is regular.","start":316.653,"stop":329.462,"duration":12.81},{"text":"That's what this means.","start":329.462,"stop":329.852,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly -- yes, yes, Mr. Justice.","start":329.852,"stop":331.137,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that means that's a rule of law and not any waiver in the sense that's something a man chooses to do.","start":331.137,"stop":337.95,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You made one statement and I didn't -- I might understand you.","start":337.95,"stop":340.962,"duration":3.01},{"text":"You said that the law issued is dependent on the facts, on the facts that (Inaudible), but no additional information for the community to the (Inaudible)","start":340.962,"stop":352.606,"duration":11.64},{"text":"Is that an evidence so far as on what (Inaudible)","start":352.606,"stop":355.528,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I -- I said that Mr. Walsh contended in his argument that no additional -- no additional facts were before the Commissioner.","start":355.528,"stop":362.881,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything --","start":362.881,"stop":363.228,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"And I say that the --","start":363.228,"stop":363.917,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the record on one side or the other as to what --","start":363.917,"stop":366.101,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, there is not, Mr. Justice Black.","start":366.101,"stop":367.736,"duration":1.63},{"text":"There is none.","start":367.736,"stop":369.51,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Murphy, what is the system or what is the factors in the federal system insofar as these complaints are concerned?","start":369.51,"stop":378.83,"duration":9.32},{"text":"Is -- is it the practice to do as you have done here merely -- merely alleged in the words of the statute?","start":378.83,"stop":386.722,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar as an independent inquiry that I undertook upon assuming this case, I -- I have been able to determine only that this is the common practice if indeed it is not the universal practice of tracking the language of a statute, provided of course the statute contains all the essential elements of the offense.","start":386.722,"stop":411.529,"duration":24.81},{"text":"Some statutes do not of course and if -- if the complaint is made out upon such a statute, it must add the necessary elements.","start":411.529,"stop":420.241,"duration":8.71},{"text":"But it's particularly appropriate, we think, that the complaint in a narcotics effects such as we have here be sufficient if it tracks the lack of the language of the statute because the statute is framed in terms of action and it also has a presumptive provision from which guilt is prima facie evidence -- evident if the proof of possession is adduced by the Government, so that when we charge as we did in this complaint here, that the defendant did receive and conceal heroine, we were in effect stating that he possessed heroine, and that is a fact.","start":420.241,"stop":468.298,"duration":48.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"There are some statements here that would hold an affidavit of this kind sufficient as a basis for arrest provided there were affidavits that had showing the fact with some particularity, is there any such law as that in Texas?","start":468.298,"stop":488.617,"duration":20.32}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I'm not sufficiently familiar with the law of Texas, Mr. Justice Black, to answer the question.","start":488.617,"stop":494.563,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Murphy, if you're satisfied on that point, why don't you just rely on your warrant as being the grounds for arrest?","start":494.563,"stop":504.958,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Government of course --","start":504.958,"stop":507.15,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that's a very simple thing if -- if you're satisfied on your law there, if it is a fact to assume a federal system to do that, it's been done for -- for many years, why do you bring a new issue into the case and try to redirect our attention to Texas law?","start":507.15,"stop":522.662,"duration":15.51},{"text":"Why don't you say the man who was -- who was armed with a federal warrant here and he saw the man and walked over and he arrested him.","start":522.662,"stop":530.526,"duration":7.86},{"text":"That's -- that's enough if you've got a good warrant, isn't it?","start":530.526,"stop":534.376,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":534.376,"stop":535.055,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, why do you -- why do you --","start":535.055,"stop":538.097,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it --","start":538.097,"stop":538.804,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- (Voice Overlap) away from that -- from that particular thing and take us into the State area?","start":538.804,"stop":544.698,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"It's undoubtedly out of an abundance of caution that we do that, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":544.698,"stop":551.086,"duration":6.39},{"text":"I would be particularly contented to stand here and defend this case upon the validity of the warrant and upon the theory that by not contesting the regularity of the warrant and the regularity of his arrest at the preliminary hearing which he waived -- he thereby waived the right to challenge the validity of his arrest.","start":551.086,"stop":572.541,"duration":21.46},{"text":"However --","start":572.541,"stop":572.84,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You needn't have to go that far if you're satisfied with your warrant, do you?","start":572.84,"stop":576.174,"duration":3.33},{"text":"The -- you know, there is no problem of waiver here if it's a good warrant, is it?","start":576.174,"stop":580.962,"duration":4.79},{"text":"So really all -- the main question here is, is that a good warrant?","start":580.962,"stop":586.311,"duration":5.35},{"text":"If it is a good warrant, no question about it from your standpoint, is it?","start":586.311,"stop":590.371,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's correct, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":590.371,"stop":592.215,"duration":1.84},{"text":"However, opinions may detour about this complaint and for that reason we contend, of course, that the arrest can still be supported on an alternative theory and that is the -- well, two alternative theories, the right of the agent to arrest him under Texas State Law, and also, the waiver theory that by not asking and receiving the preliminary hearing and he has consented to be maintained in custody and also deprived himself of the right to challenge the validity of his arrest.","start":592.215,"stop":631.283,"duration":39.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But it seems to me from your argument that you were shunning this warrant into the background and -- and for the first time in this Court raising the State issue and thrusting that forward and basing it on that.","start":631.283,"stop":644.714,"duration":13.43},{"text":"And then, if you had to get to the other to -- to put on the grounds of waiver where I -- I -- it's hard for me to see why that should be a procedure if you're satisfied with this warrant.","start":644.714,"stop":655.741,"duration":11.03},{"text":"And that -- that to me is -- is really the main part of this case.","start":655.741,"stop":661.17,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps Mr. Chief Justice, we did emphasize a -- a theory which was subsidiary to the principal one upon which we contend the -- this judgment below can be supported.","start":661.17,"stop":675.418,"duration":14.25},{"text":"However, I think they're both equally supportable and equally valid.","start":675.418,"stop":679.508,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you one more question?","start":679.508,"stop":681.312,"duration":1.8},{"text":"Assuming that you have to stand on the justification for an arrest without a warrant, in other words, assuming that we should disagree with the warrant itself, what is there in the record that adds to the officer's knowledge beyond that which is contained in the affidavit for the warrant?","start":681.312,"stop":701.545,"duration":20.23},{"text":"Is there anything more affirmative in the record?","start":701.545,"stop":704.271,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, a great deal more.","start":704.271,"stop":707.41,"duration":3.14},{"text":"At page 18 of the record which I was planning to read about two-thirds of the way down actually the testimony in point commences on page 17.","start":707.41,"stop":720.806,"duration":13.4},{"text":"But at this point the -- and this was a testimony elicited during the motion to suppress.","start":720.806,"stop":728.3,"duration":7.49},{"text":"Petitioner's counsel was attempting to show that the agent did not have a personal knowledge of the facts which he alleged in his complaint.","start":728.3,"stop":738.454,"duration":10.15},{"text":"And the agent in attempting to show that he had plenty of information upon which to seek the complaint, testified that, page 18, ?I had kept a surveillance on this man beginning the latter days of December.","start":738.454,"stop":759.668,"duration":21.21},{"text":"As I said before, he was in possession of information which corroborated my surveillance, and vice-versa, my surveillance corroborated my information that he was in Houston and planned to go to Chicago, Illinois to bring back a large supply of heroin.","start":759.668,"stop":774.129,"duration":14.46},{"text":"And he did leave.","start":774.129,"stop":775.427,"duration":1.3},{"text":"And he did return.","start":775.427,"stop":776.852,"duration":1.42},{"text":"And my surveillance did corroborate that information.","start":776.852,"stop":780.156,"duration":3.3},{"text":"In addition to that, I had received information from other law enforcement officers that he was in town with that large quantity of heroin.","start":780.156,"stop":789.081,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Now --","start":789.081,"stop":789.96,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, why don't you go on, tell about the -- after he got back from the days (Inaudible) and another car got in behind him --","start":789.96,"stop":800.936,"duration":10.98}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":800.936,"stop":801.613,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- stopped at a private place.","start":801.613,"stop":803.717,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Where?","start":803.717,"stop":804.194,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"I was just about to do that, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":804.194,"stop":807.887,"duration":3.69},{"text":"After the warrant had been obtained, Agent Finley on the following day took up surveillance outside petitioner's home, and he observed him in company with a known police character, Officer Shelton, who accompanied the agent, testified to that.","start":807.887,"stop":825.38,"duration":17.49},{"text":"And they followed the two in separate cars, the petitioner in his Cadillac automobile and this police character in a Chevrolet to another part of Houston where they stopped and engaged in conversation on the street.","start":825.38,"stop":844.333,"duration":18.95},{"text":"And after they resumed their journey, this well-known police character turned North on Lathrop Street and the petitioner turned South.","start":844.333,"stop":853.572,"duration":9.24},{"text":"The police characters went -- went one block and stopped and remained in his car.","start":853.572,"stop":859.54,"duration":5.97},{"text":"The petitioner went one block -- I'm sorry, the character went North, the petitioner went one block South to the intersection of Brownsville and Lathrop where he entered a dwelling.","start":859.54,"stop":872.29,"duration":12.75},{"text":"The officers continued their surveillance and he -- the petitioner remained inside for about one-half hour.","start":872.29,"stop":879.364,"duration":7.07},{"text":"And then, he emerged from the house and entered the garage into the rear of the building.","start":879.364,"stop":886.787,"duration":7.42},{"text":"He remained inside the garage only a few seconds and came out of the sidedoor at which time he was carrying a paper bag in his hand.","start":886.787,"stop":899.901,"duration":13.11},{"text":"Now, the agents of course approached him as he approached the gateway to the yard.","start":899.901,"stop":905.361,"duration":5.46},{"text":"And at that point, they arrested him.","start":905.361,"stop":908.655,"duration":3.29},{"text":"We --","start":908.655,"stop":909.581,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"What did they find in the paper bag?","start":909.581,"stop":911.048,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- oh, well, they found the five ounces -- six ounces of heroin and 95 paper bindles, and a quantity of both heroin as well.","start":911.048,"stop":922.483,"duration":11.43},{"text":"These facts, we say, in their totality taken together with the information that Agent Finley had, and as I said, all of the information that he had is not contained in this record.","start":922.483,"stop":936.218,"duration":13.74},{"text":"But if I may allude for a moment to the record in Number 515, which is also before this Court, the Court may see that Agent Finley had much more.","start":936.218,"stop":949.913,"duration":13.7},{"text":"He, for instance knew that a seller who was employed by the petitioner had made a sale on that very morning and various things like that.","start":949.913,"stop":963.213,"duration":13.3},{"text":"So, there is much more that could have been brought out but as I say, the Government is compelled to rely upon a record made by the petitioner, for this reason, we think it should be held to his waiver.","start":963.213,"stop":978.661,"duration":15.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Walsh.","start":978.661,"stop":988.399,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"I have only six minutes but I would like to say that if you impose upon the petitioner the waiver which the Government asks you to do, you will be creating a new kind of waiver.","start":988.399,"stop":998.316,"duration":9.92},{"text":"You will be creating a waiver in the very inception of the criminal prosecution which -- from which relief can in no way ever be granted.","start":998.316,"stop":1010.739,"duration":12.42},{"text":"In the Companion case, the Government has -- has confessed error in the case and has admitted that where a hearing on a motion to suppress is actually held that this constitutes relief from the waiver.","start":1010.739,"stop":1025.207,"duration":14.47},{"text":"And you'll find that in the Government's memorandum in the Indiviglio and Diaz case.","start":1025.207,"stop":1030.944,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Here, a hearing was held.","start":1030.944,"stop":1032.839,"duration":1.89},{"text":"The judge went ahead and ruled.","start":1032.839,"stop":1034.306,"duration":1.47},{"text":"He heard all the evidence, he went ahead and -- and ruled on the question.","start":1034.306,"stop":1037.929,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And I don't think it's fair and I don't think it's right to insist to the man on the very day after he's arrested be aware of all this legal -- his legal positions.","start":1037.929,"stop":1050.516,"duration":12.59},{"text":"If -- if he had demanded a preliminary hearing, you still wouldn't have any more of the records than you have right here because those preliminary hearings aren't reported.","start":1050.516,"stop":1058.029,"duration":7.51},{"text":"All you would have is a notation on the docket where it says \"waived hearing\" you'd have a notation saying ?hearing held.","start":1058.029,"stop":1064.186,"duration":6.16},{"text":"And the U.S. Commissioners, I point out in my brief, had no -- there was no relief that the U.S. Commissioner could give a petitioner that would be meaningful and -- and binding on anyone.","start":1064.186,"stop":1075.933,"duration":11.75},{"text":"If he let the petitioner go, the petitioner could still be rearrested.","start":1075.933,"stop":1079.125,"duration":3.19},{"text":"The Commissioner's decision is not res judicata, it doesn't bind anyone.","start":1079.125,"stop":1085.321,"duration":6.2},{"text":"And I -- I feel that a waiver should not be imposed upon a person until he is in a court or a place where he has to take action in order to get affirmative binding relief.","start":1085.321,"stop":1097.743,"duration":12.42},{"text":"In connection with the state practice, I -- I -- I feel that it is almost unfair to plunge the Court into the law of Texas because this can become even more complicated than I think the Solicitor General understands.","start":1097.743,"stop":1112.86,"duration":15.12},{"text":"We held, for instance, in Texas a statute Article 727 (a) of the Code of Criminal Procedure, that statute is not cited in the briefs by the way, which provides that any evidence obtained in violation of the laws or Constitution of the United States are not admissible in the state courts.","start":1112.86,"stop":1129.937,"duration":17.08},{"text":"And I think the provisions of the Texas Narcotic Act have to be considered in turn with the Criminal Procedure statute which adopts all of the federal rules.","start":1129.937,"stop":1145.119,"duration":15.18},{"text":"The Government said, and I think significantly, we rely upon Walker.","start":1145.119,"stop":1150.337,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The counsel said that twice.","start":1150.337,"stop":1152.72,"duration":2.38},{"text":"And I would like the Court to look at the Walker case in conjunction with all of the other cases which we have cited in our brief.","start":1152.72,"stop":1159.825,"duration":7.11},{"text":"The Walker case is a freak.","start":1159.825,"stop":1162.37,"duration":2.54},{"text":"The Walker case was a -- a collateral attack by way of coram nobis on a conviction.","start":1162.37,"stop":1168.136,"duration":5.77},{"text":"And the Court went on to hold originally that the man had no right to challenge the legality of his arrest in a collateral attack.","start":1168.136,"stop":1179.019,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Walker, where it says that this type of complaint is sufficient, relies solely on Rice versus Ames, the Supreme Court decision on the 180th U.S.","start":1179.019,"stop":1186.949,"duration":7.93},{"text":"Rice versus Ames is a foreign extradition case.","start":1186.949,"stop":1189.676,"duration":2.73},{"text":"And the Court explicitly held that it was departing from the rules that are normally applied in criminal cases because of the difficulties of bringing witnesses to this country from foreign lands to testify in connection with extradition proceedings.","start":1189.676,"stop":1204.159,"duration":14.48},{"text":"With the exception of those cases, all of the law is that this type of complaint is insufficient.","start":1204.159,"stop":1212.36,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Walsh, you could shave down the authority of Walker still more.","start":1212.36,"stop":1217.039,"duration":4.68},{"text":"In the first place, Judge Swnn said this is a collateral attack and it was -- this wasn't the way to raise it, but raised it before, but then he said, \"But, we'll go on.\"","start":1217.039,"stop":1226.913,"duration":9.87},{"text":"And he goes on and said the arrest wasn't illegal.","start":1226.913,"stop":1229.238,"duration":2.33},{"text":"But he goes on and said that it was if that's no good.","start":1229.238,"stop":1232.392,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Anyhow, the search was made of a person not the petitioner, so he has no complaints.","start":1232.392,"stop":1238.012,"duration":5.62},{"text":"I should think it's abolished, I think that authority that you can get from (Inaudible) judge.","start":1238.012,"stop":1242.225,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, Your Honor.","start":1242.225,"stop":1243.241,"duration":1.02},{"text":"And you will find that all of the other authority is -- is our way.","start":1243.241,"stop":1249.027,"duration":5.79},{"text":"This is a historical thing.","start":1249.027,"stop":1250.325,"duration":1.3},{"text":"The Government says, Well, if essential facts means one thing in Rule 7, it must mean the same in Rule 3.","start":1250.325,"stop":1255.852,"duration":5.53},{"text":"That is not so.","start":1255.852,"stop":1257.389,"duration":1.54},{"text":"The constitutional affidavit required by the Fourth Amendment goes back to the -- the days of the Writs of Assistance in James Otis in 1761.","start":1257.389,"stop":1268.845,"duration":11.46},{"text":"There is plenty of reason for construing those things differently.","start":1268.845,"stop":1271.171,"duration":2.33},{"text":"They're intended to do different things.","start":1271.171,"stop":1273.295,"duration":2.12},{"text":"And they are historically foreign to each other.","start":1273.295,"stop":1278.243,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I would like to discuss briefly of Mr. Chief Justice Warren's question about what is the federal practice.","start":1278.243,"stop":1284.878,"duration":6.63},{"text":"I don't know what the federal practice is generally, but I do know that every Court with the exception of the Walker Court that has encountered this kind of case has reversed it.","start":1284.878,"stop":1293.969,"duration":9.09},{"text":"And I know further that the reason you don't have so many cases, I will -- I will assume that the Government is in practice violating the Constitution by filing insufficient warrants.","start":1293.969,"stop":1304.482,"duration":10.51},{"text":"But the reason you don't have a lot of cases based on that is that it only makes a difference if the man is caught for something.","start":1304.482,"stop":1310.588,"duration":6.11},{"text":"Otherwise, he might just as well -- he's got no purpose to challenge the arrest.","start":1310.588,"stop":1314.518,"duration":3.93},{"text":"What -- what difference does it make to him?","start":1314.518,"stop":1317.452,"duration":2.93},{"text":"He might just as well let the proceedings go on and be indicted and defend himself.","start":1317.452,"stop":1321.304,"duration":3.85},{"text":"He doesn't have to challenge the initial process which brought him to the bar of justice.","start":1321.304,"stop":1327.031,"duration":5.73},{"text":"And because of the fact that I'm -- I'm sure it's comparatively rare that the Government is successful as they were here in catching the man because that is a comparatively rare situation, you don't have many cases.","start":1327.031,"stop":1339.871,"duration":12.84},{"text":"But I don't think that that practice which I believe to be violative of the Constitution should be encouraged.","start":1339.871,"stop":1348.994,"duration":9.12},{"text":"My time is up.","start":1348.994,"stop":1349.703,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1349.703,"stop":1349.731,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may finish --","start":1349.731,"stop":1350.827,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I say your cases are collected in your brief.","start":1350.827,"stop":1354.338,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1354.338,"stop":1354.845,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Both contrary to the Walker case on the question of whether the complaint --","start":1354.845,"stop":1358.765,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"You will find it in Appendix A on --","start":1358.765,"stop":1359.743,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- following the statutory language are sufficient?","start":1359.743,"stop":1362.817,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"You will find them in Appendix A.","start":1362.817,"stop":1364.295,"duration":1.48},{"text":"I cite six or seven cases which -- going to some reasoning on it and some of them deal with complaints that are exactly like this one.","start":1364.295,"stop":1372.791,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Furthermore, you will find more cases to this point on pages 14, 15, and 16 of the brief.","start":1372.791,"stop":1386.653,"duration":13.86},{"text":"I -- I particularly like Mr. Justice Bradley's memorandum In re Rule of Court where he was sitting as a Circuit Justice of Federal Case Number 12126 cited on page 15.","start":1386.653,"stop":1396.898,"duration":10.24},{"text":"You will see his reasoning -- he goes on at some length on why it is necessary to actually have a witness before the Commissioner and to give the Commissioner the facts or the magistrate.","start":1396.898,"stop":1407.627,"duration":10.73},{"text":"And of course, as I said earlier, the cases although that the -- that the affidavit must be self-sufficient that's the purpose of it.","start":1407.627,"stop":1415.263,"duration":7.64},{"text":"Now, it might be permissible to attach more affidavits to it but the point is that we are not expected to rely on oral communications between the officer and the magistrate.","start":1415.263,"stop":1428.079,"duration":12.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- your reputation in this case is that they require if followed, both statements of facts on which the probable cause is taken.","start":1428.079,"stop":1441.838,"duration":13.76}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, because the probable cause is the magistrate's decision, not the policemen's.","start":1441.838,"stop":1446.204,"duration":4.37},{"text":"And if you affirm this case and allow this kind of complaint to go through, you'll be delivering the unbridled authority to make arrest into the hands of the police because Mr. Finley made his own decision here, and he said so on the record.","start":1446.204,"stop":1456.993,"duration":10.79},{"text":"He said, \"I have probable cause to believe this.\"","start":1456.993,"stop":1459.448,"duration":2.46},{"text":"Well, he's not the man that's supposed to have it.","start":1459.448,"stop":1462.133,"duration":2.68},{"text":"It is to make an arrest under federal warrant.","start":1462.133,"stop":1464.316,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is customary and I think Mr. Murphy indicated, it is not customary to have stenographic units in the proceedings before the U.S.Commissioner.","start":1464.316,"stop":1473.545,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":1473.545,"stop":1474.242,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore -- therefore, it seems to me, though it's more important.","start":1474.242,"stop":1480.298,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I mentioned that in my brief.","start":1480.298,"stop":1481.883,"duration":1.59},{"text":"The federal -- I mentioned that in our brief.","start":1481.883,"stop":1483.308,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Federal court reporters are not entitled -- are not required to attend preliminary hearings.","start":1483.308,"stop":1486.272,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, all you have is what was forwarded before the Commissioner and not the supporting evidence.","start":1486.272,"stop":1492.084,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1492.084,"stop":1493.257,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1493.257,"stop":1493.277,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Walsh, on behalf of the Court, I would like to express our appreciation for you're having accepted appointment to represent this indigent defendant and for the diligence with which you have sustained that responsibility.","start":1493.277,"stop":1510.891,"duration":17.61}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'd like to --","start":1510.891,"stop":1511.211,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It's always comforting by the fact that lawyers are willing to give their time or energy to a cause -- a public cause of that kind, so we appreciate it.","start":1511.211,"stop":1520.919,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Walsh","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, your words are very generous compensation, Your Honor.","start":1520.919,"stop":1522.933,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1522.933,"stop":1523.32,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And, Mr. Murphy, we appreciate of course the diligence with you -- which you have represented the interests of our Government.","start":1523.32,"stop":1529.588,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"John L. Murphy","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1529.588,"stop":1547.163,"duration":17.58}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"May 21, 1958","petitioner":"Giordenello","respondent":"United States","docket":"549","citation":"357 US 480 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/480","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 30, 1958"}